VAILL Report: Q4 October - December, 2025

Curriculum

Mark is taught fall version of the AILP 3 credit version and will teach it again the spring.

Mark launching undergrad AI course as part of the legal studies minor in the spring.:ULAW 2542: Introduction to Artificial Intelligence in the Legal Profession

Taught AI Governance/Ethics course in October with Sean Perryman

Started VAILL practicum F’25/S’26 and Law as a Business courses. Integrating AI substantially into LAB both as a tool and its impact on the industry.

  • VAILL practicum: working on AI e-course for students and resource database (see projects, below)
  • Law as a Business: hosted Jeff Kelly and Adrianne Cleven (Nelson Mullins) to talk with students about AI in the biglaw setting and how it’s impacting all aspects of the firm’s business.

Kyle teaching Law Practice Technology course after taking over for Mark

Mark is working with Kelly Bahiraei to develop for spring:

  • MLS version of an AI/Law course with programming similar to AILP with a late spring/summer 2026 launch date

Events and Speaking Engagements

Cat and Mark conducted faculty workshop on AI in early November.

Cat and Mark gave a reunion weekend presentation to aluni in early November.

Kyle led a CLE for an in-house counsel retreat on integrating AI into your daily workflow. (Schneider Electric, Global)

Emily and Kyle led a CLE on the AI in the Business of Law at the Nashville Bar Association’s Annual Probate Symposium.

Emily led a CLE/CE on AI for estate planning professionals at the Estate Planning Council of Chattanooga.

Emily led a session on AI-assisted legal research and writing at Clio’s Legal AI Advantage Summit, attended by ~900 attorneys. Her session was rated best of the day, alongside sessions from Ed Walters, VP of Clio, and Nikki Pope, Head of Legal at Nvidia.

Mark and Emily presented to the Nashville Bar Association’s Leadership Forum on legal technology and AI for lawyers.

AI Governance Fall Event Mark, Sean Perryman and Asad Ramzanali of VPA organized an AI Governance symposium held on Oct. 21.

Coverage of event can be found:

  • https://law.vanderbilt.edu/navigating-different-paths-to-legal-careers-in-ai-and-technology-policy/
  • https://law.vanderbilt.edu/ais-energy-appetite-environmental-impacts-and-governance/
  • https://law.vanderbilt.edu/the-state-of-state-level-ai-regulation/
  • https://open.substack.com/pub/vaill/p/recapping-the-inaugural-vanderbilt?utm_campaign=post-expanded-share&utm_medium=web

Women+AI Exec Ed programming Continuing to explore a day-long exec ed course hosted at Vanderbilt in the fall or spring semester. The faculty will ideally be a mix of Vanderbilt experts (cross-disciplinary, e.g. me, Charreau Bell, Sarah Burriss) and women industry leaders. There will be a (fairly substantial) fee for participating and we envision it will generate a nice net profit. Ultimately hinges on identifying a date that works for enough of the faculty and could end up being a spring semester or summer program.

Women+AI Summit V.2 Planning is underway for version 2 of the W+AI Summit on February 7, 2026 at VLS. Working closely with Charreau Bell of DSI to design and plan.

Projects

Day in Court — Data Science for Good summer project with DSI: the “winning” team in the Hacking Pro Bono event is building out their proposed tool we’re calling Day in Court to help self-represented litigants manage court appearances successfully, with the help of DSI’s summer program team. The non-technical project team includes the VAILL team, 2 LAS attorneys, a USB in-house attorney, 2 VU undergrads, and a VLS student. Summer session wrapped up in August. Currently discussing with Legal Aid and DSI how to move the project forward at this point.

GenAI e-Training for Legal Aid of North Carolina: partnering with LANC’s innovation lab to create a version of the VAILL e-course for legal aid attorneys and staff who are new to genAI. We anticipate scaling this for use by any LSO — working with LSNTAP to scale, may be a practicum project. The initial project was completed in August. Working now to scale. OpenAI + Legal Aid Collaboration: LANC’s Innovation Lab is officially partnering with OpenAI on legal aid-specific tools and Cat is advising on the collaboration. Exploring the expansion of the collaboration to include Legal Aid of Middle Tennessee — they are not as far along in their genAI exploration so this may require some foundation-laying. AI State Legislative Tracker: Team completed its work and presented at the summer AI showcase. A small team will continue to work on additional improvements and features, in conjunction with a new tracker project described below, but we will start promoting this tool more now. Current version is here: https://vaill-legislation-tracker.hf.space/

  • Mark created a companion tracker looking at which laws are most at risk for targeting by the Trump preemption EO: https://ai-state-legislation-with-eo-risk.streamlit.app/

Lawfare AI Litigation Tracker Project - The same team that is working on the legislation tracker is prototyping the litigation version in partnership with Lawfare. After showing the tracker to a colleague at lawfare, their team was impressed by it and asked to partner on a version of it that would track various AI litigation data. They have already collected much of the data and we can repurpose our codebase to build something reasonably quickly. Team is meeting twice a week to build the tracker.

  • This project will continue on in the spring but beta site is available here: https://ai-state-legislation-with-eo-risk.streamlit.app/
  • Mark created a companion app creating a dashboard that visualizes the data: https://ai-litigation-dashboard.streamlit.app/

AI Resources Database: Fall practicum project to complete the resource database collection and curation and start user-testing an interface.

Exploring genAI for Law Students with VAILL: law student-focused version of the email course — fall practicum project. Will launch this semester. Experiment with a new delivery method for online courses that we can expand and potentially create an income stream for VAILL.

VALIANT collaborations: Mark is now an AI Fellow with VALIANT. No specific projects but we’ve been meeting with them regularly and we’ve been lecturing at various events. This opens door to formalize future projects. VAILL Substack, The AI of Law: continuing to share about work that VAILL and the team are doing, with increasing subscriptions and promotion in other media, including two mentions in the TaxProf Blog.

Mike Vandenbergh AI Energy Consumption/Governance Research

Mike’s paper which Mark is a co-author on with others: Unplugging the Artificial Intelligence Energy Emergency was accepted for publication by the Texas Environmental Law Review

Separate Private Governance paper now has a target of January cycle to give Mike more time to add in additional sections but still very much moving forward.

Mike Vandenbergh — AI Climate and Environmental Twin Working on a potential project as a collab between VAILL and the PCG Lab (and potentially DSI and/or VALIANT) to design and build an “AI application or twin that can mimic an individual who is progressive, liberal, moderate, conservative, or libertarian. The AI twin will enable researchers, lawyers, business managers, advocacy group managers, and policymakers to test messages regarding beliefs, behavior, and policy support to better understand the wide range of responses that are likely to occur.” Hoping to make this a project with the DSI.

Meetings

Mark:

NACD AI Governance/Healthcare Governance Planning Group:

Based on the success of the event last spring, members of NACD, Ernst and Young and Vanderbilt are in early stages of planning a similar event for next spring. Currently meeting monthly.

Cat:

  • TEDLaw monthly faculty advisory group meeting
  • LANC Innovation Lab meeting re: OpenAI collaboration
  • Women+AI Summit 2.0 planning underway
  • Ryan McKenney (VLS ‘15): Ryan has relocated to Nashville and seeks a more active role as an adjunct and VAILL supporter, including through his company Quantinuum — exploring ideas for cross-VU (and TN) collaboration
  • TN Supreme Court has issued an order seeking public comment on regulatory and licensure changes — meeting regularly with a small group of lawyers across TN who seek to support changes that would expand access to legal help, specifically through the use of technology. Note that we are not supporting the Court’s exploration of ending ABA accreditation.
  • Multiple meetings to prep for upcoming CLE presentations and speaking events

Kyle has been meeting and establishing relationships with various tech vendors in order to get access to the products for VAILL and classroom usage (Everlaw and Luminance).

Unclear what is happening with this project at the moment.

Registration launched in February; dedicated website will launch in March.

Current Status: Underwent another round of revisions and has been resubmitted for IRB feedback but there is still a lot of enthusiasm for this project.

Coursera Course: Mark is focusing on finalizing updates to the current course and hopes to re-record a few portions soon pending time commitments on library-related responsibilities. The program also aims to identify and mitigate inherent biases present in training data and search for ways to implement algorithmic fairness and bias mitigation techniques to ensure that AI models are fair and unbiased, including continuous monitoring for emergent biases as the AI model learns from new data. The study can be found here: https://www.vals.ai/vlair (VAILL team is credited at the bottom.)

AI State Legislative Tracker: Team is meeting twice a week and has made great progress. We are working with the same DSI lead that worked on the Climate Governance Lab’s project and it turns out that much of the code used for that project can be used for ours. Mike Vandenbergh AI Energy Consumption Research

I was originally just adding comments related to AI Governance frameworks and providing background on the minutiae of how GenAI systems work, but eventually wound up in a co-author situation.

Mike, Jane and Mark are also pursuing a grant application as an extension of Jane’s research regarding consumer-based uses and how it might relate to carbon disclosures. Mark will mostly be in the role of explaining the tech side along with monitoring the emerging private and public governance frameworks and how they do or don’t currently address environmental concerns.

VAILL: March 2024 update

1. Course Development & Delivery

a. Coursera Course

  • Mark finalized recording content for the Coursera course. The course is currently in post-production with target of an April launch.

b. Short Courses

  • Hosted Ryan McKeney for Quantum short course.

c. New Course Development

  • Developing new course for approval: "Access to What" exploring the growing civil justice crisis and how technology and especially AI can be used to help solve the crisis.
  • VAILL practicum and AI in the Workplace short course (taught by Emily Lamm) approved (we think)

2. Research Initiatives

a. DSI Collaboration: "Human Nature" Project

Ongoing collaboration with Charreau Bell of DSI for the Owen Jones "Human Nature" project, analyzing Supreme Court data for patterns in discussions on human nature. The project is a pilot leveraging supreme court data to use LLMs in detecting patterns in how the subject of human nature is discussed over time. The subject itself is out of our traditional scope, but this partnership with DSI could be a permanent vehicle for various VAILL initiatives.

b. University of Alabama Birmingham PartnershipAI Judicial-Decision-Making Tool

Partnering with Brandon Blankenship and an interdisciplinary team of University of Alabama Birmingham researchers, who are developing a small proposal for developing an AI tool that performs Judicial-Decision-Making and accurately generates well-structured Orders with explanations that allow human scrutiny of the basis of the decision. The program also aims to identify and mitigate inherent biases present in training data and search for ways to implement algorithmic fairness and bias mitigation techniques to ensure that AI models are fair and unbiased, including continuous monitoring for emergent biases as the AI model learns from new data. VAILL will tentatively provide expertise in reviewing outputs during the fine-tuning process and perhaps access to compute through DSI's servers. This is an ambitious proposal that may not work and that we are supporting on the margins, but was worth at least exploring involvement in.

a. Legal Problem Solving Course Projects

  • Overseeing Legal Problem Solving course projects: collaboration with Legal Aid of North Carolina; AAA; VU OGC; VLS Immigration Clinic.

c. Guest speakers

  • Co-hosted John Nay

d. External engagement

  • Mark met with Nam Nguyen, an NLP PhD student at UCLA who has a start-up designed to detect hallucinations in AI-generated legal documents.

a. Advisory Council

  • Onboarding VAIL advisory council members — working through process of organizing and deploying advisors on projects.

  • Onboarded fellow Lae Cantimbuhan.
